Lets make this method more c oriented.&lt;br/&gt; 
Maybe now its more clear that there are two branches&lt;br/&gt; 
1. When n equals 1 - which stops the recursion.
2. Otherwise - multiply the current value of n by the result of calling the fact method with n - 1, which eventually becomes 1 and stops the recursion.

    def fact(n:Int): Int=
    { 
        if (n == 1) {
           (return) 1;
        }
        else {
           (return) n * fact(n - 1);
        }
    }

The semicolon is redundant and the the a return keyword is not recommended/necessary.&lt;br/&gt;
You can read about it [here][1]


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12560463/return-in-scala

So you are left with:

    def fact(n:Int): Int=
    { 
        if (n == 1) {
           1
        }
        else {
            n * fact(n - 1)
        }
    }

Which is basically the same as:

    def fact(n:Int): Int=
    { 
        if (n == 1) 1;
        else n * fact(n - 1)
    }

